\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Compositionality and Context-Dependency in Natural Language Semantics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Peter Blouw
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Accounting for the fact that many linguistic expressions seem to take on
 different meanings in different contexts is a central problem in the philosophy
 of language.
 The standard solutions to this problem involve either (a) relabelling most
 forms of context-sensitivity as a pragmatic rather than semantic phenomena,
 or (b) using compositional rules to create formal representations of meaning
 that only take on definite values in a particular contexts.
 In this paper, I evaluate complaints against both approaches.
 The issue in the case of (a) is that the problem of accounting for context-sens
itivity is simply punted into the domain of pragmatics where it is left
 largely unsolved.
 The issue in the case of (b) is that the semantic rules used to generate
 meanings become intractably numerous once their behavior is uniquely defined
 for each possible context.
 Because of these issues, I argue that a constraint-based linguistic formalism
 recently used describe adjective-noun combinations offers a better approach
 to describing how meanings of phrases and sentences can be both compositional
 and context-dependent at the same time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The principle of compositionality states that the meaning of a complex expressio
n is fixed by its syntactic structure and the meanings of its simpler parts
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Szabo:2012a,FodorLepore:1991"

\end_inset

.
 In the study of natural language semantics, this principle is typically
 taken to entail that expressions such as phrases and sentences are interpreted
 in the following two-step manner 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Recanati:2012"

\end_inset

: first, a set of a lexical rules are used to assign meanings to simple
 expressions; then, a set of composition rules are used to combine these
 simple meanings into the meaning of a phrase or sentence.
 A compositional semantics for a language is accordingly given by a finite
 number of instances of the following two rule schemes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 175-76"
key "Recanati:2012"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
