 is a syntactic operation that combines simple or complex linguistic expressions
, and
\shape italic
 g
\shape default
 is semantic operation that maps the meanings of the inputs to a syntactic
 operation
\shape italic
 
\shape default
to the meaning of its output 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "see also"
key "Szabo:2012b"

\end_inset

.
 Conventional wisdom states that if natural languages were not compositional
 in the manner spelled out by (1) and (2), it would be impossible to explain
 the capacity of language users to produce and comprehend indefinitely large
 numbers of sentences 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Szabo:2012a,Szabo:2012b"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nonetheless, an important challenge to the idea that natural languages are
 compositional arises from the fact that many expression types seem to take
 on different meanings in different contexts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Recanati:2005,Unnsteinsson:2014"

\end_inset

.
 Consider, for example, the following sentence:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Mike finished John's book
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Recanati, 2004, p.
 62)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is highly plausible that the proposition expressed by this sentence can
 vary depending on whether Mike finished reading the book or finished binding
 it 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Recanati:2005"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The genitive construction 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

John's book
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can also exhibit variation depending on whether, for instance, John wrote
 the book or John owns the book.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 But if the verb 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

finished
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is assigned a fixed meaning as per (1), then it is not clear how to account
 for this variation, since it cannot be attributed to a change in syntactic
 structure or a modification of the lexical constituents in the sentence.
 Many philosophers accordingly think that certain verbs like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

finish
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 make context-sensitive semantic contributions to the sentences in which
 they occur 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CappelenLepore:2005"

\end_inset

.
 Similar reasoning has been used to produce arguments favoring the context-sensi
tivity of a wide range of expressions containing quantifiers, gradable adjective
s, counterfactual conditionals, and various philosophically loaded terms
 such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

knows
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CappelenLepore:2005"

\end_inset

.
 The status of these arguments is controversial, but they highlight an important
 philosophical problem: there are good reasons for thinking that meanings
 are compositional 
\shape italic
and
\shape default
 context-sensitive, yet there are equally good reasons for thinking they
 cannot be both.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, I evaluate two general approaches to solving this problem.
 The first approach, referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

minimalism
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, preserves the standard picture of compositionality while appealing largely
 to pragmatics to account for the apparent context-sensitivity found in
 natural language 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CappelenLepore:2005"

\end_inset

.
 The second approach, referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

contextualism
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, revises the standard picture of compositionality to allow features of
 context to influence the behavior of certain lexical rules and composition
 rules 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Recanati:2005,Recanati:2012"

\end_inset

.
 I evaluate typical formulations of both approaches and conclude that they
 are inadequate.
 The problem with minimalism is that it makes semantics largely irrelevant
 to an explanation of human communication 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Recanati:2005"

\end_inset

, while leaving pragmatics largely mysterious.
 The problem with contextualism, highlighted by Unnsteinsson (2014), is
 that it often involves introducing new parameters into rules such as (1)
 and (2) that simply bring about some observed form of context-sensitivity.
 This simply amounts to relabelling context-sensitivity as parameter-sensitivity.
 Moreover, by redefining the behavior of each rule in each possible context,
 the inclusion of these parameters has the implausible consequence of requiring
 competent language users to have knowledge of an intractably large number
 of rules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of these problems, I favor an alternative approach that assigns
 a meaning to a complex expression by optimally satisfying a set of constraints
 that are introduced by the expression's simpler constituents and its context
 of utterance.
 This approach has two important benefits: first, it accounts for the observatio
ns about communication that motivate both minimalism and contextualism;
 and second, it accounts for these observations using a relatively small
 number of theoretical entities.
 Of course, the use of constraint-based formalisms in the development of
 linguistic theory is not a novel idea 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "see e.g.,"
key "PrinceSmolensky:1997,SmolenskyLegendre:2006a"

\end_inset

.
 But it is novel, to my knowledge, to propose that such a formalism can
 offer a promising solution to the philosophical problem of understanding
 how natural languages can be both context-sensitive and compositional at
 the same time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is an outline of the rest of the paper.
 First, I provide a critical analysis of standard contextualist and minimalist
 views.
 Second, I use this critical analysis to motivate the use of a constraint-based
 approach to linguistic theorizing that has largely been ignored by philosophers.
 For concreteness, I discuss an application of this approach to the semantics
 of privative adjectives (Oliver, 2014), and suggest how this sort of applicatio
n could be generalized to a wider range of expression types.
 Third, I revisit the phenomena that motivate contextualism and minimalism
 and argue that these phenomena are naturally handled using ranked constraints.
 I conclude that a constraint-based approach to natural language semantics
 is viable and promising alternative to the status quo.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Minimalism and Contextualism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minimalism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Minimalism is the view that the semantic content expressed by a word or
 sentence is largely invariant across contexts.
 In more concrete terms, the view can be summarized by the following claims
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "pp. 2-3, 144-45"
before "see"
key "CappelenLepore:2005"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{itemize} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
\backslash
item [a.] Semantic context sensitivity is restricted to a basic set of expression
s that includes the standard indexicals and little else.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
\backslash
item [b.] Outside of this basic set, the semantic content of a expression
 
\backslash
textit{e} is shared by all utterances of 
\backslash
textit{e}.
  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{itemize}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For present purposes, it is helpful to think of minimalism as a view that
 fits very closely with the picture of compositionality presented in (1)
 and (2).
 The reasons for favoring minimalism are accordingly similar to the reasons
 for favoring compositionality.
 In short, minimalism explains how we are able to use indefinite numbers
 of sentences across indefinite numbers of contexts without undertaking
 the impossible task of memorizing rules for each sentence and context.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cappelen and Lepore (2005) provide a recent and influential defense of minimalis
m.
 Their argument is comprised of the following three claims.
 First, anyone who posits context-sensitivity 
\shape italic
somewhere
\shape default
 outside of the basic set of expressions has to posit context sensitivity
 
\shape italic
everywhere
\shape default
 in order to remain consistent.
 Radical contextualism, in short, is the only viable form of contextualism.
 Second, radical contextualism is an implausible view.
 It rules out the possibility of people understanding one another's utterances.
 Third, minimalism is only view that is able to explain how people are able
 communicate the same proposition across a variety of different contexts.
 A successful defense of these claims warrants the conclusion that minimalism
 is preferable to contextualism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is helpful to consider each claim in a bit more detail.
 To establish that moderate forms of contextualism inevitably collapse into
 radical contextualism, Cappelen and Lepore primarily make use of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

context shifting arguments
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 designed to illustrate how different uses of the same expression can state
 different things.
 To give an example, consider the sentence 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

There is no 1984 Bordeaux left
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This sentence might express something true in a context involving a restaurateu
r checking the inventory of her wine cellar, but it might express something
 false in the context of a discussion of wines that are currently available
 on the world market.
 Contextualists routinely make this kind of argument to establish that a
 certain expression type is context sensitive.
 The problem, according to Cappelen and Lepore, is that if these arguments
 can be used to illustrate that some sentences are context sensitive, then
 they can be used to illustrate that 
\shape italic
all
\shape default
 sentences are context sensitive.
 For instance, it is straightforward to develop a context shifting argument
 that applies to an arbitrary expression such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

John went to the gym
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (2005, p.
 44).
 In different contexts, this expression could mean that John walked to the
 gym, that John exercised at the gym, or that John oversaw a construction
 job at the gym.
 To concede that context-shifting arguments can be generated for arbitrary
 sentences is to concede radical contextualism.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
One point to note here is that the presence of linguistic phenomena such
 as ambiguity, vagueness, polysemy, metaphor, and syntactic ellipsis needs
 to be ruled out in order to infer any genuine form of context-sensitivity
 from a context-shifting argument 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 42"
key "CappelenLepore:2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem with radical contextualism, in turn, is that it requires speakers
 to have shared access to numerous contextual features in order to understand
 one another.
 These contextual features include things like the topic of prior conversation,
 the identities and goals of the speakers, the surrounding environment,
 and anything else that could put to use in a context-shifting argument
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 123-24"
key "CappelenLepore:2005"

\end_inset

.
 If the presence or absence of a given contextual feature can make the differenc
e between a person saying 
\shape italic
x
\shape default
 and saying 
\shape italic
y
\shape default
, then speakers need to have shared access to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

complete
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 collection of contextual features in order to successfully disambiguate
 the content expressed by a particular sentence.
 Yet speakers rarely, if ever, have such shared access to such features,
 so it becomes unclear how the radical contextualist can explain their ability
 to communicate with one another.
 The resulting argument against radical contextualism is simple: if context
 plays a pervasive role in determining what is said, then people would not
 be able to effectively communicate; yet people clearly are able to effectively
 communicate, so it must not be true that context plays a pervasive role
 in fixing what is said.
 As such, radical contextualism is false.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This argument leads to directly to Cappelen and Lepore's third claim in
 favor of minimalism.
 Their view is that each sentence expresses a context invariant 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

minimal proposition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that is generated through rules like (1) and (2).
 Since these minimal propositions can be interpreted through the application
 of a finite number of semantic rules known to all competent language users,
 they ensure that speakers are able to successfully communicate the same
 contents across different contexts.
 For example, Cappelen and Lepore claim that an utterance of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The apple is red
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 expresses the minimal proposition < the apple is red > regardless of whether
 the context of utterance favors an interpretation on which the flesh rather
 than the skin of the apple is said to be red.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Just to clarify, red apple flesh might be salient in a context in which
 people are looking for apples infected with a fungus that stains the normally
 white flesh red.
 See Cappelen and Lepore (2005, p.
 111) for details about the example.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A listener need not be aware of this context in order to understand what
 has been said.
 Her knowledge of the semantic rules of english allow her to easily conclude
 that the speaker has stated that 
\shape italic
the apple is red
\shape default
, full stop.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What, then, is one to make of the observations that motivate philosophers
 to argue that there is widespread semantic context-sensitivity in natural
 language? Cappelen and Lepore respond by briefly outlining a view - 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

speech act pluralism
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - on which every utterance expresses a minimal proposition along with an
 indefinite number of 
\shape italic
other
\shape default
 contents.
 These other contents are what shift across the conditions described in
 standard context-shifting arguments, but it is not the job of a semantic
 theory to give an account of them.
 Rather, it is the job of a theory of speech acts.
 And speech acts, on Cappelen and Lepore's view, resist simple analysis.
 They argue that what is stated by a particular utterance can depend on
 facts unknown to the speaker entirely.
 For example, if John says 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

My boss is running the marathon next week
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and John's boss also happens to be sixty years old, then it is true, on
 Cappelen and Lepore's view, that John has stated that a sixty year old
 is running the marathon next week, even if John is completely ignorant
 of his boss's age.
 Generalizing from this kind of example leads Capellen and Lepore to conclude
 that every utterance expresses an indefinite number of propositions.
 Moreover, they concede that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

there might not be 
\shape italic
any
\shape default
 systematic theory from which one can derive all which is said by an utterance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (p.
 200, original emphasis).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two major problems in Capellen and Lepore's analysis that I wish
 to highlight.
 The first concerns their description of the conditions under which communicatio
n is possible.
 Their argument against radical contextualism, recall, claims that if context
 can make a difference to the meaning of essentially any sentence, then
 successful communication can only occur on the implausible condition that
 speakers have shared access to exactly the same context.
 I think that this argument relies on drawing a false dichotomy between
 perfect communicative success and complete communicative failure.
 Consider once more an utterance of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

John went to the gym
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 A person who hears this utterance while ignorant of the fact that John
 manages a construction project at the gym will not be entirely misinformed.
 They will be able to correctly answer certain questions (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Where is John?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), draw certain inferences (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

John is not at home
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), and plan certain actions (e.g.
 meet John at the gym later in the day).
 On the other hand, a person who does have relevant background information
 about John might be able to answer further questions (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Is John working?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) and draw further inferences (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

John is probably wearing his construction outfit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), but these additional communicative results can characterized in terms
 of one person having a richer understanding of the content expressed by
 the utterance.
 Context, in short, often functions to supplement or modify the contents
 conventionally expressed by particular sentence types.
 Speakers are aware of this fact and accommodate it.
 They ask questions to resolve confusion (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What is John doing at the gym?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), and they supply additional information when a lack of shared context
 is apparent (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

John went to the gym to manage his construction crew
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Overall, context-sensitivity presents a manageable obstacle to communication,
 not a complete roadblock.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second major problem concerns Cappelen and Lepore's choice to label
 (most) context sensitivity as a pragmatic phenomenon.
 Their description of speech act pluralism commits them to a view on which
 speech act content is radically context sensitive.
 But if so, then communication should be just as hard for them to explain
 as it is for those who think that 
\shape italic
semantic
\shape default
 content is radically context sensitive.
 The issue here is that if speakers need mutual access to a context in order
 to share semantic contents, then they should also need mutual access to
 a context in order to share speech act contents.
 To explain, suppose 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

John went to the gym
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 semantically expresses the proposition < John worked out at the gym > in
 one context, and the proposition < John walked to the gym > in another
 context.
 Suppose too, along with Cappelen and Lepore, that language users would
 not be able to identify the proposition semantically expressed by this
 sentence unless they know all the facts about the context of utterance.
 If so, then the threat of miscommunication is apparent.
 Unfortunately, this line of reasoning is equally persuasive (or unpersuasive)
 if we simply make reference to speech act content instead of semantic content.
 Suppose an utterance of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

John went to the gym
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is used to assert that John worked out at the gym.
 The content of this assertion is the proposition < John worked out at the
 gym >.
 Alternatively, suppose the utterance is used to assert that John walked
 to the gym.
 Now the content of the assertion is the proposition < John walked to the
 gym >.
 As before, if language users do not know all the facts about the context
 of utterance, then they will not be able to determine which speech act
 has been performed.
 The threat of miscommunication is now just as apparent as it was before.
 Overall, Cappelen and Lepore's speech act pluralism faces 
\shape italic
exactly
\shape default
 the same problems that lead them to reject radical contextualism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Minimalism, in summary, is a view that is attractive because it preserves
 the standard picture of compositionality (and its attendant explanatory
 benefits) by pushing the burden of explaining context sensitivity onto
 a theory of pragmatics.
 But absent a satisfying pragmatic account of context-sensitivity, this
 strategy is suspiciously reminiscent of gerrymandering.
 A main goal of linguistic theory is to elucidate the relationship between
 context and content, and minimalism simply abandons this goal within the
 domain of semantics while failing to pick up the slack within the domain
 of pragmatics.
 Speech act pluralism offers no precise explanations of how utterances involving
 quantifiers, counterfactual conditionals, genitives, and gradable adjectives
 communicate different contents in different contexts.
 Given such a state of affairs, perhaps it is better to reconsider the possibili
ty that features of context widely influence the behavior of the semantic
 rules that assign contents to sentences.
 This is precisely the approach that many contextualists adopt.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Contextualism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contextualism is the view that semantic context sensitivity is present in
 numerous expressions outside of the basic set of indexicals.
 One starting point for developing a contextualist view is the observation
 that many sentences cannot be assigned complete propositions through semantic
 rules like (1) and (2).
 For example, a genitive construction like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Paul's car is fast
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is arguably only truth-evaluable if the nature of Paul's relation to the
 car is specified 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 62"
before "see"
key "Recanati:2005"

\end_inset

.
 This relation might involve ownership (e.g.
 Paul owns the car), temporary possession (e.g.
 Paul rents the car), desire (e.g.
 Paul wants to drive the car), selection (i.e.
 Paul cheers for the car during a race), or any number of other things.
 Furthermore, a rule like (2) cannot specify the relation in question because,
 on the standard assumption that semantic composition occurs via function
 application, the combination of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Paul's
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

car
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must always return the same semantic value.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Unless, of course, there is lexical ambiguity involving the terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Paul
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

car
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

s
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 (A lexicalization of the possessive construction is assumed here following
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Carpenter:1997"

\end_inset

).
 Positing such ambiguity does not have much prima facie plausibility.
 Another option would be treat 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Paul's car
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as Kaplanian character (i.e.
 a function from contexts to contents) - Recanati's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Recanati:2012"

\end_inset

 approach is along these lines.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 So unless 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Paul's car
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 implausibly refers to the same car in all contexts, the sentence 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Paul's car is fast
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is not the sort of thing that can be true or false in the absence of contextual
 elaboration.
 Observations of this kind suggest that the compositional machinery favored
 by minimalists is simply not up to the task of developing a complete semantics
 for natural language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recanati (2004) offers a well-known defense of contextualism.
 His arguments are motivated by two complementary observations.
 On the one hand, the contents assigned to sentences through rules like
 (1) and (2) can fail to specify a complete proposition, as in the above
 example.
 By arguing that this sort of failure is a universal phenomenon (i.e.
 that sentences never express determinate propositions in the absence of
 contextually salient background assumptions), Recanati aims to show that
 the notion of a linguistically mandated, minimal proposition is incoherent.
 On the other hand, even if minimal propositions exist, they are almost
 never cognitively accessible to language users and therefore have no role
 to play in theories of linguistic communication.
 Overall, Recanati thinks that context is what makes up the difference between
 incomplete and complete propositions in the first case, and between psychologic
ally unavailable and available propositions in the second case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In developing these arguments, he primarily focuses on the issue of psychologica
l availability.
 As such, it is helpful to condense his position into the following two
 claims:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{itemize} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
\backslash
item [a.] What is said by a sentence in a given context (i.e.
 its content) must be cognitively available to normal language users (Recanati,
 2004, p.
 20).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
\backslash
item [b.] What is cognitively available to normal language users cannot determine
d without appeal to top down processes that transform the contents assigned
 to words and phrases by linguistic convention.
   
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{itemize}
\end_layout

\end_inset

It should be clear that these claims are tension with the view that meanings
 are determined in a compositional manner.
 Put simply, compositionality enforces a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bottom up
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 determination of meaning in accordance with linguistic convention, while
 Recanati's availability constraint requires the presence of additional
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

top down
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 effects that introduce things like background assumptions, speaker intentions,
 and world knowledge into the determination of an expression's content 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 139"
key "Recanati:2005"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The notions of bottom up and top down processes might seem a bit vague here,
 but the basic idea is that a bottom up process is linguistically specified
 and mandatory, while a topic down process is pragmatically specified and
 optional.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How persuasive is the first claim that an expression's content must be cognitive
ly available to normal language users? By and large, Recanati's argument
 involves an appeal to increased explanatory insight.
 In numerous examples, what speakers are conscious of having said is not
 what the traditional semanticist defines as such.
 Take, for instance, the expression 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I have already eaten breakfast
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 8"
key "Recanati:2005"

\end_inset

.
 According to the semanticist, the content of this expression is a proposition
 that is true just in case the speaker has eaten breakfast at least once
 in the past.
 Yet in ordinary circumstances, the speaker would claim to have said no
 such thing (and a listener would likewise claim to have heard no such thing).
 Rather, what is cognitively available to both the speaker and the listener
 is the proposition that the speaker has had breakfast 
\shape italic
today
\shape default
.
 Overall, if one wishes to explain these psychological properties of language
 users, then one needs a notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

what is said
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that makes doing so possible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is where Recanati's second claim becomes important.
 He views the assignment of a cognitively available proposition to a linguistic
 expression as a process that is influenced by a combination of mandatory
 and optional processes referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

saturation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

modulation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Saturation, to explain, is the linguistically controlled assignment of
 a context-sensitive semantic value to an expression 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 7"
key "Recanati:2005"

\end_inset

.
 To give a standard example, the indexical expression 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a variable takes on different semantic values in different
 contexts via saturation.
 Moreover, the assignment of a value to the variable follows a simple linguistic
 convention: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to the speaker, regardless of any extralinguistic facts.
 Similar conventions apply for indexicals such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

now
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

here
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which refer to the time and place of utterance, respectively.
 As such, saturation is a process controlled by the rules of language.
 Moreover, saturation is mandatory, since sentences containing unsaturated
 constituents fail to express complete propositions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Modulation is a different phenomenon on both counts.
 It is the process by which the content assigned to a particular expression
 is adjusted in an optional manner by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

top down
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 processes.
 For example, in the case of the sentence 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I've had breakfast
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, a typical modulation would involve extending the content of the sentence
 to include a temporal qualifier (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I've had breakfast 
\shape italic
today
\shape default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 This kind of extension behavior is referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

free enrichment
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Other forms of modulation include 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

loosening
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in which the extension of a predicate is expanded to include more things
 (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The city is 
\shape italic
asleep
\shape default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; p.
 34, emphasis added), and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

semantic transfer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in which an expression takes on a new referent that is related to its
 typical referent in some contextually salient way (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\shape italic
The ham sandwich
\shape default
 left without paying
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, spoken in the context of a dine-and-dash; p.
 26).
 The most important thing to note about all of these examples is that there
 are no specific rules that mandate particular modulations in particular
 situations.
 For example, a sentence like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The city is asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 might in one case be modulated such that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the city
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to the inhabitants of a city, while 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 remains unmodulated.
 In another case, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 might be modulated to mean something 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quiet and inactive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the city
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 remains unmodulated.
 The choice between these two options depends on the background assumptions
 and intentions of the speakers, not on the rules of english.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To return now to the point at issue, Recanati defense of the second claim
 is essentially an enumeration of examples in which modulations are required
 to get from the minimal proposition associated with a particular sentence
 to the cognitively available one.
 Some of these examples, such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I've had breakfast
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, have already been discussed.
 Other, more interesting examples involve situations in which the processes
 of saturation and modulation are interdependent on one another.
 For instance, Recanati (2004, p.
 61-64) offers an extended discussion of a hypothetical scenario in which
 five gladiators are each made to fight a wild animal, one of which is a
 lion.
 The gladiators wear decorative shields, and one gladiator's shield depicts
 a roaring lion.
 The scenario concludes with each animal lying dead with a gladiator's sword
 through its body.
 Afterwards, Recanati imagines an utterance of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Bring me the lion's sword - I want to have a look at it
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (p.
 63), and notes that this utterance is ambiguous.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 could refer either to the dead animal or the warrior with a lion on his
 shield.
 In the former case, the possessive construction will pick out a relation
 that holds between an animal and a sword that killed it, while in the latter
 case, the possessive construction will pick out a relation that holds between
 a warrior and the sword he or she used.
 If modulation favors a non-literal interpretation of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, then the possessive construction must be saturated to indicate the relation
 between warrior and weapon.
 On the other hand, if saturation favors a relation between an animal and
 a sword, then 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must be left unmodulated.
 The upshot of this example is that mandatory process of specifying the
 nature of the possessive relation between lion and sword cannot be carried
 out in isolation from the optional process of modifying the referent of
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This interdependence of these processes, one traditionally thought of as
 semantic and the other pragmatic, casts considerable doubt on the minimalist's
 claim that semantic interpretation is strictly prior and independent of
 pragmatic interpretation.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What is said
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by Recanati's imagined utterance cannot,be determined by the rules of language
 alone.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If this argument is persuasive, a remaining challenge concerns the fact
 that modulation is not easily reconciled with a compositional explanation
 of linguistic understanding.
 To deflect this criticism, Recanati 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "Recanati:2012"

\end_inset

 proposes a view on which rules like (1) and (2) are modified to incorporate
 parameters that are sensitive the context of use.
 These context parameters, in turn, signal which saturations and modulations
 ought to play a role assigning a semantic value to a particular linguistic
 expression.
 For instance, to account for saturation, Recanati (2012, p.
 188-89) considers the following revised compositional rule schemes: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{itemize} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
\backslash
item [1a.] $I(e)_c=f(c)=m$ 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
\backslash
item [2a.] $I(f(e_{1},
\backslash
,e_{2}))_c=g(I(e_{1})_{c1},
\backslash
,I(e_{2})_{c2})$  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{itemize}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The first scheme can be read as describing the interpretation of expression
 
\shape italic
e
\shape default
 in context 
\shape italic
c
\shape default
, and defines a higher-order interpretation function that returns a mapping
 from contexts to meanings for all simple expressions in the language.
 The second scheme is equivalent to (2) except insofar as the arguments
 to the semantic composition function 
\shape italic
g
\shape default
 are context-dependent as per (1a).
 To illustrate the application of these rule schemes, consider again the
 example of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I already ate breakfast
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 has a function from contexts to contents as its meaning; this function
 returns different contents when different speakers utter the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The other expressions (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

already
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, etc.) are by assumption in no need of saturation, so they are interpreted
 in the usual manner.
 However, (1a) and (2a) are consistent with minimalism, since they roughly
 schematize a compositional semantics that incorporates Kaplanian characters
 for handling indexicals.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Something slightly more sophisticated is required to account for the modulations
 that differentiate minimalism from contextualism.
 Recanati's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
after "p. 189-90"
key "Recanati:2012"

\end_inset

 proposal is to introduce a higher-order function, 
\shape italic
mod
\shape default
, that takes expression-context pairs as arguments, and returns a function
 that maps from meanings to meanings as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula $mod(e,c)=g_{ec}:m\rightarrow m$
\end_inset

, where 
\shape italic
m
\shape default
 is the domain of semantic values 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "see also"
key "Unnsteinsson:2014"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
One could make this approach more sophisticated by typing the semantic values
 as in Carpenter (1997).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 With this modulation function in place, a further revision to the basic
 rule schemes of (1) and (2) is provided:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{itemize} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
\backslash
item [1b.] $I(e)_c=mod(e,c)f(c)=g_{ec}(m)=m'$ 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

	
\backslash
item [2b.] $I(f(e_{1},
\backslash
,e_{2}))_c=g(I(e_{1})_c,
\backslash
,I(e_{2})_c)$  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{itemize}
\end_layout

\end_inset

As a brief word of explanation, these rule schemes allow each (potentially
 complex) constituent in a linguistic expression to modulated in a unique
 way.
 The benefit of this generality is that modulations can occur with arbitrary
 syntactic scope.
 For example, a modulation might apply to a simple constituent (e.g.
 the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the city is asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) or an entire sentence (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I've had breakfast
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 One can likewise imagine modulations that apply specifically to noun phrases,
 prepositional phrases, and a variety of other syntactic categories.
 Overall, if this account of compositionality is plausible (and Recanati's
 earlier claims concerning the cognitive availability of what is said are
 convincing), then there is little reason not to adopt a contextualist position.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The major problem with Recanati's proposal lies in fact that a context parameter
, 
\shape italic
c
\shape default
, is passed as an argument to every function corresponding to a semantic
 rule (i.e.
 every instance of (1b) and (2b)).
 As Unnsteinnson (2014, p.
 3340-41) notes, this entails that each rule's behavior is defined uniquely
 for each context.
 The behavior of 
\shape italic
mod
\shape default
, for example, is defined uniquely for each possible expression-context
 pair, returning a specific modulation function, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{ec}$
\end_inset

, for each such pair.
 If this is true, then understanding a language implausibly requires memorizing
 an infinite number of rules to go along with the infinite number of possible
 contexts in which the expressions of the language might be used.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In defense of Recanati, one might suppose that the possible context parameters
 are abstract and few in number.
 But in this case, Unnsteinsson notes that the proposal simply fails to
 offer any explanatory insight.
 To explain, if 
\shape italic
mod
\shape default
 delivers the contextually appropriate modulation function for every linguistic
 expression, then the behavior of 
\shape italic
mod
\shape default
 simply restates the contextualist assumption that linguistic expressions
 can have their meaning affected by features of context.
 The context parameters, 
\shape italic
c
\shape default
, do all of the heavy lifting, and Recanati is silent on what is included
 in these parameters.
 Are they speaker intentions? Background assumptions? If so, how are they
 represented? Overall, Unnsteinsson is right to argue that introducing context
 parameters throughout the rules defining a language's semantics is too
 general an approach to be explanatory.
 Put simply, the strategy amounts to little more than relabelling context-sensit
ivity as parameter-sensitivity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Minimalists and contextualists are best thought of as providing different
 solutions to the same problem.
 The minimalist proposes to account for context-sensitivity using the tools
 of speech act theory.
 The contextualist, on the other hand, proposes to account for context-sensitivi
ty by adding a rich store of modulations into semantic theory.
 These differences aside, there are aspects of both positions that are clearly
 correct.
 The minimalist, in my view, is right to highlight the fact that each simple
 linguistic expression contributes some constant ingredient into the determinati
on of an utterance's content.
 If this were not true in some broad sense, one would be stuck with the
 implausible conclusion that the words used in an utterance place no constraint
 on its content.
 Where the minimalist goes too far is in supposing that words place 
\shape italic
inviolable
\shape default
 constraints on this content.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The contextualist, on the other hand, is quite right to highlight the communicat
ive irrelevance of minimal propositions.
 If a main goal of semantics is to explain linguistic communication, then
 a semantics that describes utterances in terms of contents that are unrecogniza
ble to language users is simply inadequate.
 The minimalist tries to avoid this problem by gesturing towards an account
 of pragmatics that maps context-invariant semantic contents onto context-sensit
ive speech act contents.
 But as Recanati illustrates, it is nearly impossible to enforce this clean
 separation between semantics and pragmatics.
 If one thinks of semantic content as the result of saturation and speech
 act content as the result of modulation, then it is clear from examples
 like the phrase 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the lion's sword
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that semantic and pragmatic interpretation are mutually dependent processes.
 The former is not strictly prior to the latter.
 Something along the lines of Recanati's revised composition schemes is
 evidently needed.
 The drawback of these schemes is they give rise to a situation in which
 the behavior of every semantic rule is different in every context.
 What is needed, then, is a framework that allows both linguistic expressions
 and features of context to mutually constrain the assignment of content
 to an utterance without extravagantly multiplying the entities that impose
 these constraints.
 The optimization-based approach described in the next section, I argue,
 can meet this challenge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Optimization and Semantic Composition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of Recanati's most important insights is that interpretation of one
 constituent in a sentence can constrain the interpretation of another.
 Recall the sentence 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The city is asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the city
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is interpreted metonymically, then 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must be interpreted literally.
 On the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the city
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is interpreted literally, then 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must undergo loosening.
 One way to think about this phenomenon is to suppose that there a set of
 candidate semantic values for each expression, and that a process of constraint
 satisfaction selects the candidates that minimizes the degree to which
 the constraints in question are being violated.
 Recanati (2004) hints at this idea, but does not pursue it in much detail:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
In the model I have in mind, the literal meaning of [an] expression is accessed
 first and triggers that activation of associatively related representations.
 That literal meaning is a natural candidate for the status of semantic
 value, but there are others: some of the representations activated by associati
on activate further candidates for the status of semantics value.
 All candidates, whether literal or derived, are processed in parallel and
 compete.
 When an interpretation that fits that broader context of discourse is found,
 it is selected...and the other candidates are suppressed.
 (p.
 28)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relationship between these ideas and the more formal notions that underlie
 Recanati's approach to compositionality is not clear.
 It is hard, for instance, to interpret rules like (1b) and (2b) as performing
 the kind constraint satisfaction described in the above quote.
 Fortunately, there are other tools that one can use to describe the process
 by which an optimal semantic value is chosen from amongst a set of candidates.
 The framework of optimality theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "PrinceSmolensky:1997"

\end_inset

 offers a powerful way to describe linguistic phenomena in terms violable
 patterns and soft tendencies rather than hard and fast rules.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Optimality Theory 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In brief, optimality theory characterizes a speaker's knowledge of a language
 in terms of a set of soft constraints on the well-formedness of linguistic
 structures.
 This approach contrasts with more traditional formalisms in which well-formedne
ss is measured in a binary fashion.
 A standard context-free grammar, for example, consists of a set of symbolic
 rewrite rules that generate all and only the sentences (or parse trees)
 that belong to a language.
 A categorial grammar of the sort described by Carpenter (1997) behaves
 in much the same way: a sequence of words either admits of a derivation
 of a particular lambda term expressing its meaning, or it does not.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An optimality-theoretic grammar, by comparison, scores parse trees (or lambda-ca
lculus expressions; see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Oliver:2014"

\end_inset

) along a continuum and in accordance with a set of constraints.
 Prince and Smolensky's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "PrinceSmolensky:1997"

\end_inset

 motivation for adopting this approach is that the linguistic structures
 comprising a language often exhibit conflicting tendencies.
 For example, they note that English sentences tend to display a pattern
 in which a subject clause is followed by a verb, which is in turn followed
 by an object clause.
 This pattern is not universal, though.
 The sentence 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What did John see?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (p.
 1604), for instance, places the object rather than the subject first.
 Arguably, this is because a constraint favoring the placement of question
 words like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

what
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at the beginning of sentences is stronger than the constraint favoring
 subject-verb-object word order.
 The key conclusion drawn from theses observations is that, in many instances,
 no possible linguistic structure can satisfy all relevant constraints.
 Producing a syntactically well-formed utterance, as such, involves selecting
 a linguistic structure that violates fewer constraints than any other structure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimality-theoretic analyses can be tailored to a number of different domains,
 but all such analyses exhibit a few properties in common 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SmolenskyLegendre:2006a"

\end_inset

.
 First, there is an input to be analyzed and mapped to an output.
 Second, there is candidate space that defines a number of possible outputs
 for the input under consideration.
 In a standard parsing task, for example, the input would an English sentence,
 and the candidate space would consist of a set of potential parses of the
 sentence.
 Third, a collection of ranked constraints is used to evaluate each candidate
 and assign it a score.
 To be precise, each constraint can be thought of as function that defines
 a mapping between candidates and scores 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Oliver:2014"

\end_inset

.
 Each candidate's total score is the sum of all the scores assigned to it
 by these mappings.
 The scores, in turn, assign an ordering to the set of candidates, and the
 top-most element in this ordering is selected as the optimal output for
 the input under consideration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "PrinceSmolensky:1997"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, the constraint set used to evaluate the candidate space is partially
 contingent on the nature of the input.
 Or put another way, different inputs introduce different constraints into
 the evaluation process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Composition with Constitutive Material Adjectives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Oliver (2014) uses optimality theory to explain how different kinds of adjective
s combine with nouns to create simple noun phrases like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

big city
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cold beverage
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Four adjective types are discussed.
 An 
\shape italic
intersective
\shape default
 adjective combines with a noun to pick out a set of entities that is within
 the extension of both the noun and the adjective (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

red apple
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 A 
\shape italic
subsective
\shape default
 adjective combines with a noun to pick a set of entities that is a subset
 of the extension of the noun (e.g.
 
