A number of the candidate classes are ruled out because they contain nothing
 (these candidates are marked with a struck-out row letter).
 Of the remaining candidates (f) and (h), the highest ranked one is (f)
 .
 As such, the optimization process produces as its output a representation
 that picks out a class of entities that are made of stone and have the
 appearance of a lion (i.e.
 the combined expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\lnot A(x)\wedge L(x)\wedge\lnot O(x)\wedge S(x)$
\end_inset

 ).
 In short, the optimization process produces a representation that correctly
 refers to stone lions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But what if an alternative ranking is chosen in which the constraints supplied
 by the noun take precedence over the constraints supplied by the adjective?
 In this case, the highest ranked class of entities in the first stage of
 the analysis would be those entities referred to by the expression 
\shape italic

\begin_inset Formula $A(x)\wedge L(x)\wedge O(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\shape default
The second stage of analysis is thus restricted to rule out any candidates
 that conflict with this initial result (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S(x)$
\end_inset

 is removed from consideration since it would result in an empty extension).
 As such, the selected output is a representation that simply refers to
 the equivalence class of entities that are lions not made of stone (i.e.
 
\shape italic

\begin_inset Formula $A(x)\wedge L(x)\wedge O(x)\land\lnot S(x)$
\end_inset


\shape default
.
 This is clearly an undesirable result, but simply stipulating that adjectival
 constraints take precedence over nominal constraints is an ad-hoc solution,
 and worse, might not generalize to other composite expressions.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In fact, nominal precedence is the norm (Oliver, 2014).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Oliver's response to this problem is to propose a metaconstraint that requires
 each constituent in a composite expression to contribute something to the
 complex whole of which it is a part.
 This meta-constraint favoring 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

full interpretation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Oliver, 2014, p.
 69) forces a ranking in which the constraints associated with the adjective
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stone
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 take precedence over the constraints associated with the noun 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stone
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 would otherwise make no semantic contribution to the meaning of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stone lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It helps at this point to compare the proposal developed by Oliver with
 the accounts of constitutive material adjectives mandated by minimalism
 and contextualism.
 Absent some postulation of semantic ambiguity concerning the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, the minimalist seems forced to concede that the minimal semantic value
 associated with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stone lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the empty set of stone lions.
 Moreover, the explanation of how 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is interpreted by ordinary speakers to mean something like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

representation of a lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must be pushed into the domain of pragmatics.
 It is not clear what form such an explanation ought to take.
 One option would be to appeal to an assumption concerning communicative
 relevance that would rule out a literal interpretation of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Choosing this option, though, leaves unanswered the question of 
\shape italic
why 
\shape default
relevance favors a non-literal interpretation of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The contextualist, on the other hand, is forced to rely on composition rules
 like (1b) and (2b).
 One way to use these rules to explain the difference between privative
 and intersective noun-adjective combinations is to appeal to context parameters.
 In stone-related contexts, for instance, the meaning of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is modulated to describe representations of lions.
 Another option would be to simply ignore context parameters and note that
 if adjectives are treated as functions from nouns to nouns (as in Carpenter,
 1997), then an adjective such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stone
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be defined as function that behaves, as it were, privatively when combined
 with nouns like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and intersectively when combined with nouns like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wall
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Both of these explanations are inadequate for reasons already discussed.
 The problem is that they introduce new theoretical assumptions to explain
 new semantic phenomena on a roughly one-to-one basis.
 To explain, if new context-parameters or new function definitions are introduce
d into a semantic theory to account for each new phenomenon, then the theory
 runs the risk of having a parameter per observation it is intended to explain.
 Such flexibility is undesirable, since it prevents the theory from being
 restricted in any way by linguistic data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of the optimization-based approach, however, there is no needless
 growth in theoretical assumptions.
 Oliver's account requires only two: a lexical semantics that provides basic
 constraints, and a single meta-constraint that favors rankings that allow
 every input into the composition process to make a semantic contribution
 to the output.
 It is fair to say that this account of adjective-noun combinations is more
 explanatory and less ad-hoc than the available alternatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
More General Forms of Composition in Context
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I wish to now suggest that Oliver's approach generalizes to handle a number
 of the phenomena that are of interest to minimalists and contextualists
 alike.
 I consider three of Recanati's examples: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The city is asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I've already had breakfast
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Give me the lion's sword
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 These examples cover the phenomena of loosening, free enrichment, and semantic
 transfer respectively.
 If they can be handled without having to redefine the behavior of some
 set of semantic rules on an ad hoc basis, then there is good reason to
 favor a constraint-based approach over Recanati's alternative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of the first example, it is worth noting that Oliver's treatment
 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stone lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 essentially uses optimization to perform loosening on the extension of
 the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Thus, a similar explanation of loosening for the constituents in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the city is asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 ought to suffice.
 To start, it is helpful make some assumptions about the constraints introduced
 by both 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the city
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 For simplicity, suppose that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 imposes two constraints: that a denoted object is (a) in a state of unconscious
 slumber, and (b) exhibiting little activity.
 Suppose, furthermore, that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the city
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 imposes a slightly richer set of constraints: that the denoted object is
 comprised of (a) numerous buildings, (b) numerous roadways, and (c) numerous
 residents.
 The composition of these constituents via the copula 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

is
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 yields a semantic value that attributes the properties associated with
 sleeping to an entity made up of buildings, roads and people.
 But roads and buildings clearly cannot be in an unconscious slumber, so
 there is a conflict amongst the constraints that must be resolved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If precedence is given to the constraints introduced by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, then candidate semantic values satisfying the constraints preferring roads
 and buildings will be ruled out.
 Alternatively, if the precedence is given to the constraints introduced
 by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the city
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, then candidate semantic values satisfying the constraints preferring slumberin
g will be ruled out.
 The full-interpretation meta-constraint does not discriminate between these
 two alternatives, so it is necessary to appeal to something else.
 My suggestion is to appeal to a different meta-constraint that is sensitive
 to the topic of prior discourse.
 Roughly, this meta-constraint favors a ranking that gives precedence to
 those linguistic constituents that are most related to the topic of conversatio
n.
 So, in sleep-focused conversations, the constraints associated with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 would be evaluated first.
 In city-focused conversations, the reverse would hold.
 More, of course, needs to be done to flesh out the details of this proposal,
 but it is not ad hoc.
 Plausibly, a topic-driven meta-constraint would account for similar constructio
ns such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the nation is asleep
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the city is jubilant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the school is rioting
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, amongst others.
 Postulating this single meta-constraint is, overall, much simpler than
 redefining the behavior of a set of semantic rules each time a new context
 is encountered.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To handle the case of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I've already had breakfast
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, one needs to suppose that the space of candidate semantic values includes
 candidates that specify temporal qualifications (e.g.
 today, yesterday, last year etc.).
 A natural place to introduce the constraints that specify these qualifications
 is through the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

already
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Presumably, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

already
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 introduces constraints consistent with a number of different temporal specifica
tions concerning the clause it modifies.
 These constraints might track standard times such as today, yesterday,
 last week, last month, or last year.
 As such, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

already
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 would favor all semantic values that specify a time range as part of their
 truth conditions.
 To further favor the correct time range (i.e.
 today), one can also suppose that event-terms (e.g.
 breakfast, Sunday mass, a birthday, etc.) impose constraints favoring a
 particular frequency of occurrence or a particular time of occurrence.
 For instance, breakfast is something that happens daily, while a birthday
 is something that happens yearly.
 Under these assumptions, a candidate semantic value that takes into account
 the qualifier 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

today
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is automatically preferred, since all the values corresponding to other
 qualifiers violate the constraint concerning frequency of occurrence imposed
 by the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

breakfast
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Again, these lexical assumptions are both simple and general.
 For instance, they correctly predict that a sentence such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I've already had my birthday
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 would be enriched to express the proposition < I've already had my birthday
 this year >.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third case, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Give me the lion's sword
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, can actually be handled in much the same way as the first case.
 To explain, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, can be assumed to introduce at least two constraints into the interpretation
 process in the scenario described by Recanati: first, that the optimal
 semantic value refers to a large, furry animal, and second, that it refers
 to a warrior with a lion-decorated shield.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Sword
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, on the other hand, can be assumed to introduce a single constraint: that
 the optimal semantic value refers to a sword.
 The possessive 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

's
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, finally, can be taken to favor a semantic value that predicates possession
 of the referent of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sword
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the referent of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Under these assumptions, if the constraint introduced by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the lion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that favors large furry animals is ranked more highly than the constraint
 that favors the warrior with a lion-decorated shield, then the optimal
 semantic content will be one which refers to sword that has impaled the
 lion.
 Alternatively, if the relative ranking of these constraints is reversed,
 then the optimal semantic content will be one which refers to the sword
 used by the warrior.
 Again, postulating a meta-constraint sensitive to the topic of prior discourse
 provides a natural way to choose between these options: in lion-focused
 conversations, the first ranking is preferred; in warrior-focused conversations
, the second ranking is preferred.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall, my suggested analyses of Recanati's examples are not meant to be
 complete.
 Much additional work would be needed to provide address these examples
 with a rigor comparable to that used in Oliver's (2014) discussion of noun-adje
ctive combinations.
 This lack of rigor should not be misconstrued as a major weakness though.
 For one thing, neither Recanati nor Cappelen and Lepore provide detailed
 formal analyses of specific linguistic expressions to provide support for
 their claims.
 This is because questions about how such analyses ought to be carried out
 are prior to questions about the analyses themselves.
 Since my discussion, like theirs, is focused on more foundational questions,
 it should be judged by the same standards.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In keeping with these standards, there is a simple way to think about the
 advantage offered by adopting an optimization-based approach.
 When two or more linguistic expressions are composed in a particular context,
 a configuration of input variables (i.e.
 a set of simple meanings and contextual features) are being mapped to an
 output variable (i.e.
 a complex meaning).
 On a rule-based approach, each possible configuration of the input variables
 is mapped to an output by a unique rule.
 This 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

particularism
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 3340"
key "Unnsteinsson:2014"

\end_inset

 prevents knowledge of how to treat one input configuration from generalizing
 to other input configurations.
 In short, every case of linguistic composition is, implausibly, a special
 case.
 On an optimization-based approach, by comparison, each variable in the
 input favors a particular output under 
\shape italic
all
\shape default
 circumstances.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that favoring a particular output under all circumstances is simply
 the definition of what a constraint is.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To match each configuration of inputs to an output, one simply needs to
 know the value of each variable and then optimize over a set of candidates
 using the constraints introduced by these values to find the correct output.
 As such, one needs to only learn a finite number of constraints along with
 single process for performing optimization in order to display linguistic
 competence.
 Since the demands imposed on language users by a rule-based theory are
 so much greater, the choice to favor a constraint-based theory is a well-motiva
ted one.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is uncontroversially true that speakers can use the same words to say
 different things in different contexts.
 Correctly explaining how this is true is a problem that has occupied philosophe
rs for decades.
 Their proposed solutions typically involve defining rules or functions
 that bring about some observed form of context-sensitivity, either in the
 performance of a speech act or in the assignment of a semantic value.
 Sometimes these rules are stated generally enough to avoid problems associated
 with the learnability of language.
 For example, a rule that composes adjectives and nouns via set intersection
 is general in that it applies regardless of the choice of a particular
 adjective or noun.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note too that even this rule is not entirely general, given the existence
 of privative adjectives.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 But in the case of context-sensitive rules, no such generality is forthcoming.
 Cappelen and Lepore (2005, p.
 200) explicitly doubt the possibility of an algorithmic procedure that
 determines which speech acts are performed by a given utterance in a given
 context.
 Recanati (2012) is more hopeful concerning his own rule-based approach
 to semantics, but Unnsteinnson's critique suggests that the rules in question
 do little to explain linguistic context-sensitivity in the absence of some
 specification of 
\shape italic
how
\shape default
 they behave differently in different contexts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on these challenges, I have tried to motivate a different kind of
 strategy that seems not to have received much attention in the philosophical
 community: using a finite number of constraints coupled with a finitely
 specified optimization procedure to define a potentially infinite number
 of context-sensitive mappings between simple semantic inputs and complex
 semantic outputs.
 More to the point, this strategy sets out a fairly clear roadmap for the
 development of precise accounts of how context plays a role in the process
 of semantic composition.
 Lexical features impose constraints on how lexical constituents are combined
 - this accounts for the compositionality of linguistic understanding.
 Contextual features impose restrictions on the order in which these lexical
 constraints are ranked - this accounts for the context sensitivity of linguisti
c understanding.
 Contextual features might also impose constraints akin to lexical constraints,
 and thereby more directly influence the composition process.
 Working out the details of how these constraints must be organized to account
 for specific linguistic phenomena is a task for another day, but the considerat
ions offered in this paper hopefully merit the conclusion that it is a task
 worth pursuing.
 
\end_layout

